In this kata you will create a function that takes a list of non-negative integers and strings and returns a new list with the strings filtered out.

Example
filter_list([1,2,'a','b']) == [1,2]
filter_list([1,'a','b',0,15]) == [1,0,15]
filter_list([1,2,'aasf','1','123',123]) == [1,2,123]


=========================
My code:

function filter_list(l) {
  // Return a new array with the strings filtered out
  var list =[];

  for ( i =0; i<l.length ; i++){
    if ( typeof(l[i]) === "number"){
      list.push(l[i]);
    };

  };
  return list;

};


============================
Best practise
function filter_list(l) {
  return l.filter(function(v) {return typeof v == 'number'})
}
=================================================
What Is .filter()?
.filter() is a built-in array method in JavaScript. It lets you loop through an array and keep only the items that pass a test.
Think of it like a smart sieve:
- You give it a test (called a callback function)
- It runs that test on every item
- It returns a new array with only the items that passed

ðŸ§  Breaking Down the Callback: item => typeof item === "number"
This is an arrow function. Itâ€™s shorthand for:
function(item) {
  return typeof item === "number";
}


Letâ€™s dissect it:
ðŸ”¹ item
- This is a placeholder for each element in the array l
- As .filter() loops through the array, it passes each element into this function as item
ðŸ”¹ typeof item === "number"
- This is your test condition
- It checks if the current item is a number
- If true, .filter() keeps it
- If false, .filter() skips it


